nserted"> Lecturer and researcher in mathematics applied to biology and med=
icine at the Universit=C3=A9 Claude Bernard Lyon 1 and senior lecturer and =
researcher at the Institut Camille Jordan <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-n=
g-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Key takeaway=
s <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-l=
ine ng-star-inserted"> &nbsp;Algorithms are biomimetic systems, since they =
are closely linked to the way neurones work. <!----><!----></p><p _ngconten=
t-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Biomimicr=
y is used in development of many algorithms, such as =E2=80=9Cgenetic=E2=80=
=9D algorithms and convolutional (or recurrent) neural networks. <!----><!-=
---></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-=
inserted"> Inspired by humans, researchers have sought to improve the speed=
 of algorithms by adding an =E2=80=9Cattention layer=E2=80=9D to neural net=
works. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-t=
ext-line ng-star-inserted"> The challenge for the future is to reduce the e=
nergy footprint of these innovations. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3=
059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Biomimetics is n=
o stranger to the rapid progress and breathtaking performance of today=E2=
=80=99s algorithms. But the IT community is still struggling to integrate t=
he true power of the living world: its energy efficiency. <!----><!----></p=
><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserte=
d"> Biomimetics has been part of the history of algorithmics since its earl=
iest developments. =E2=80=9CIn 1964, the first neural network, the perceptr=
on, was already biomimetic. It sought to reproduce the electrophysiological=
 properties of neurons, their excitability and ability to transmit informat=
ion=E2=80=9D, explains Cl=C3=A9ment Viricel, lecturer at Lyon University. E=
ach neuron receives data, evaluates it and produces a result according to t=
he function specified in the algorithm. This process constitutes the =E2=80=
=9Cactivation=E2=80=9D of the artificial neuron, just as a neuron is activa=
ted in the brain by nerve impulses. In the perceptron, the neurons were con=
nected in a single layer. It was by multiplying the layers of neurons that =
it processed the flow of information. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3=
059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Neural networks =
<!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-lin=
e ng-star-inserted"><!----><br _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"ng-s=
tar-inserted"><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-t=
ext-line ng-star-inserted"> From the 1990s onwards, training algorithms ado=
pted these neural networks in an attempt to reproduce the way in which huma=
ns learn. =E2=80=9CNeural networks are biomimetic because they learn by err=
or, rather like humans or babies. Plasticity can be represented by matrices=
 whose elements are weighted according to success. The coefficients play th=
e role of reinforcement between neurons=E2=80=9D, explains Laurent Pujo-Men=
jouet. Clement Viricel adds, =E2=80=9CFor example, when learning a language=
, humans often discover the meaning of a word through context. Semantics pl=
ay a crucial role. This is what neural networks began to do, by being train=
ed with texts in which a word was missing. Then they were optimised by back=
propagation=E2=80=9D. In other words, by correcting the weights of the inpu=
t neurons according to the output results. =E2=80=9CBut this process is a b=
lack box, where the variations in weighting that enable the algorithm to ev=
olve are not visible,=E2=80=9D adds Cl=C3=A9ment Viricel. And we know that =
it=E2=80=99s difficult to trust a process if you don=E2=80=99t understand h=
ow it works. These methods are a major headache for underwriters in charge =
of products that incorporate them, such as autonomous vehicles1&nbsp;or dia=
gnostic assistance systems2. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=
=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Biomimicry contributes to=
 the development of a large number of algorithms. These include so-called =
=E2=80=9Cgenetic=E2=80=9D algorithms, which are based on phylogenetic trees=
 for calculation purposes, and enable the most relevant result to be select=
ed according to several methods (by rank, tournament, adaptation, etc.). Sy=
stems such as these have been deployed in search of optimums, but also in t=
he development of games, such as the famous Super Mario, to rank the player=
s amongst themselves. There are also convolutional neural networks, inspire=
d by the human visual network. =E2=80=9CIts developers wanted to reproduce =
the way in which the eye analyses an image. It=E2=80=99s a square of neuron=
s, which scan the image to capture the pixels before reconstructing it in i=
ts entirety=E2=80=9D, explains Cl=C3=A9ment Viricel. This tool is renowned =
for having surpassed the expert eye, particularly in the diagnosis of melan=
oma3. How does it work? =E2=80=9CDuring the training period it extracts cha=
racteristics such as =E2=80=98tumour shape=E2=80=99 and =E2=80=98tumour siz=
e=E2=80=99. Then it looks for these characteristics to recognise a particul=
ar object=E2=80=9D, explains Cl=C3=A9ment Viricel. <!----><!----></p><p _ng=
content-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"><!--=
--><br _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"ng-star-inserted"><!----></p=
><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserte=
d"> These biomimetic algorithms are applied to all subjects, as exemplified=
 by recurrent neural networks. =E2=80=9CThey are used to analyse data seque=
ntially or over time.&nbsp; It is widely used for automatic processing of t=
exts, by taking word order into account. Dense layers are recurrent so that=
 the network doesn=E2=80=99t forget what it has done before=E2=80=9D, expla=
ins Cl=C3=A9ment Viricel. Such networks have been used to build machine tra=
nslation tools. A first recurrent network =E2=80=9Creads=E2=80=9D and encod=
es the text in the original language, a second recurrent network decodes th=
e text in another language, all of which takes time and energy. =E2=80=9CTh=
ey require a lot of energy to train=E2=80=9D, admits Cl=C3=A9ment Viricel. =
<!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-lin=
e ng-star-inserted"> Transformers <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c30590=
05111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"><!----><br _ngcontent=
-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"ng-star-inserted"><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng=
-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> So, we need t=
o be able to learn faster. Specialists therefore devised a way of reproduci=
ng lexical dependency: when a human learns a text, they implicitly know wha=
t each pronoun refers to. This makes sentences lighter. =E2=80=9CTo reprodu=
ce this, we had to add an extra layer of neurons, the attention layer. And =
this is the parameter on which the latest biomimetic evolution has taken pl=
ace=E2=80=9D, explains the specialist. The inventors of these new artificia=
l intelligences have titled their article =E2=80=9CAttention is all you nee=
d=E2=80=9D. In fact, their network consists of just 12 layers of attention =
and an encoder/decoder system. These networks are called =E2=80=9Ctransform=
ers=E2=80=9D, and are the models used by Google=E2=80=99s Bert and Bloom, t=
he Hugging Face start-up founded by three Frenchmen. (Chat-)GPT is a direct=
 descendant of the transformers, although it has only the decoder and no en=
coder. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-t=
ext-line ng-star-inserted"> This whole story is a good example of how biomi=
metics has fed into algorithmic innovation, while forgetting one of the ess=
ential characteristics of living organisms: energy efficiency. For example,=
 training GPT=E2=80=913 Cat required 1.287 MWh and emitted 552 tonnes of CO=
24&nbsp;=E2=80=9CUntil now, developers haven=E2=80=99t been at all interest=
ed in the energy footprint of their networks=E2=80=9D, admits Cl=C3=A9ment =
Viricel. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s a skills problem. The people who design the =
algorithms are not the same people who build the physical components. We fo=
rget the machine aspect. Recent tools consume an enormous amount of power=
=E2=80=A6 and the next systems, TPU or HPU, won=E2=80=99t be any more envir=
onmentally friendly,=E2=80=9D explains the specialist. <!----><!----></p><p=
 _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted">=
 The change could come from the next generation of programmers. =E2=80=9CWe=
 are seeing the emergence of a movement in the community to address this is=
sue. On the one hand, this is due to the need to optimise energy consumptio=
n, but also for ethical reasons. For the moment, the improvements are purel=
y mechanical, based on energy transfer=E2=80=9D, explains Cl=C3=A9ment Viri=
cel.&nbsp; But other avenues are emerging, such as zero-shot shock zero-sho=
t learning algorithms: =E2=80=9CThey work without training, which saves on =
the cost of learning=E2=80=9D, adds the specialist. It remains to be seen w=
hether their performance can compete with that of their predecessors to pro=
duce totally biomimetic systems. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c305900=
