d31e02ab3" dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"--animation-duration: 400ms; --fade-animati=
on-function: linear;"><p data-sourcepos=3D"1:1-1:239">This article discusse=
s how biomimicry, the practice of drawing inspiration from nature, has sign=
ificantly influenced the development of algorithms, particularly in the fie=
ld of artificial intelligence. Here's a breakdown of the key points:</p><ul=
 data-sourcepos=3D"3:1-25:0">
<li data-sourcepos=3D"3:1-5:122"><strong>Biomimicry in Early Algorithms:</s=
trong>
<ul data-sourcepos=3D"4:5-5:122">
<li data-sourcepos=3D"4:5-4:97">The concept of biomimicry has been present =
since the early stages of algorithm development.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"5:5-5:122">The perceptron, one of the first neural ne=
tworks, aimed to replicate the electrophysiological properties of neurons.<=
/li>
</ul>
</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"6:1-9:135"><strong>Neural Networks and Human Learning=
:</strong>
<ul data-sourcepos=3D"7:5-9:135">
<li data-sourcepos=3D"7:5-7:99">Neural networks are biomimetic because they=
 learn through trial and error, similar to humans.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"8:5-8:145">They use matrices and weighted coefficient=
s to simulate the reinforcement of connections between neurons, mirroring h=
uman brain plasticity.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"9:5-9:135">Neural networks are trained using backprop=
agation, which involves adjusting the weights of input neurons based on out=
put results.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"10:1-13:133"><strong>Various Biomimetic Algorithms:</=
strong>
<ul data-sourcepos=3D"11:5-13:133">
<li data-sourcepos=3D"11:5-11:99">"Genetic" algorithms draw inspiration fro=
m phylogenetic trees for optimization and selection.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"12:5-12:91">Convolutional neural networks mimic the h=
uman visual system's image analysis process.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"13:5-13:133">Recurrent neural networks process sequen=
tial data, similar to how humans process language, and are used in machine =
translation.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"14:1-17:55"><strong>Transformers and Attention Layers=
:</strong>
<ul data-sourcepos=3D"15:5-17:55">
<li data-sourcepos=3D"15:5-15:162">To improve algorithm speed and efficienc=
y, researchers have added "attention layers" to neural networks, mimicking =
how humans focus on relevant information.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"16:5-16:137">Transformers, a type of neural network u=
sing attention layers, have led to significant advancements in natural lang=
uage processing.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"17:5-17:55">GPT models are descendants of transformer=
 models.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"18:1-21:96"><strong>Energy Efficiency Concerns:</stro=
ng>
<ul data-sourcepos=3D"19:5-21:96">
<li data-sourcepos=3D"19:5-19:136">Despite their performance, current algor=
ithms, particularly large language models like GPT-3, have a significant en=
ergy footprint.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"20:5-20:93">There's a growing awareness of the need t=
o reduce the energy consumption of algorithms.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"21:5-21:96">Researchers are exploring methods such as=
 zero-shot learning to improve energy efficiency.</li>
</ul>
</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"22:1-25:0"><strong>Future Directions:</strong>
<ul data-sourcepos=3D"23:5-25:0">
<li data-sourcepos=3D"23:5-23:107">There is a growing movement within the p=
rogramming community to address the energy consumption of AI.</li>
<li data-sourcepos=3D"24:5-25:0">The development of more energy efficient a=
lgorithms is a goal for future programmers.</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul><p data-sourcepos=3D"26:1-26:231">In essence, the article highlights t=
he successful application of biomimicry in algorithm development, while als=
o emphasizing the importance of addressing the energy efficiency challenges=
 associated with these powerful technologies.</p></div></message-content><!=
