 _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted">=
 Key takeaways <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D=
"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Biomimicry is a method of conception th=
at requires an understanding of biological systems at all scales. <!----><!=
----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star=
-inserted"> This vision of innovation has an ecological dimension: energy s=
ufficiency, adaptability, and sustainability. <!----><!----></p><p _ngconte=
nt-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> However,=
 =E2=80=9Cbiomiwashing=E2=80=9D is undermining the credibility of this conc=
ept in favour of commercial interests, without any real scientific basis. <=
!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line=
 ng-star-inserted"> In order to discuss the future and challenges of biomim=
icry, CEEBIOS and MNHN have created a programme to bring together laborator=
ies and industrialists. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D""=
 class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Creating adhesives as strong a=
s those of a gecko, threads as solid as spider silk, molecular detectors wi=
th the precision of a shark=E2=80=99s sense of smell =E2=80=93 these are so=
me of the possibilities afforded by biomimicry. But that=E2=80=99s not all =
because, beyond the sensationalism of certain products inspired by nature, =
biomimicry is also part of an ethos and a global approach to innovation. =
=E2=80=9CBiomimicry begins with an understanding of biological systems, bot=
h on a molecular level and in natural environments. The knowledge acquired =
can then be transferred to other fields of application, so it is first and =
foremost a design method. It=E2=80=99s also a philosophy,=E2=80=9D explains=
 Kalina Raskin, Managing Director of Ceebios (Centre d=E2=80=99=C3=A9tudes =
et d=E2=80=99expertise en biomim=C3=A9tisme). <!----><!----></p><p _ngconte=
nt-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> =E2=80=
=9CThis approach involves drawing inspiration from living things to devise =
solutions compatible with ecological factors,=E2=80=9D agrees Emmanuel Dela=
nnoy, a pioneer of biomimicry in France and a specialist in biodiversity. =
=E2=80=9CLiving things offer a set of specifications that are relevant to t=
oday=E2=80=99s economic and ecological challenges=E2=80=9D, he adds. This i=
s because they depend on the renewal of raw materials and store CO=E2=82=82=
 in a very energy-efficient way. =E2=80=9CLiving organisms only produce mat=
erials from atoms that are in plentiful supply, at ambient temperature and =
pressure, and with a very high degree of material circularity,=E2=80=9D exp=
lains Kalina Raskin. =E2=80=9CLife forms have adapted to all environments a=
nd constraints. Sustainability is the key issue in this long history of co-=
evolution,=E2=80=9D adds Emmanuel Delannoy. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent=
-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> This appro=
ach has already led to the development of products that will soon be on the=
 market, such as propulsion systems inspired by the movements of fish (EEL =
Energy=E2=80=99s tidal turbines1, FinX=E2=80=99s motors2&nbsp;and even Corw=
ave=E2=80=99s heart pumps3), products for agriculture based on microalgae (=
CarbonWorks=E2=80=99 CO=E2=82=82 capture systems4, Immunrise=E2=80=99s anti=
fungals5&nbsp;and Algosource=E2=80=99s bioactive ingredients6) or insects (=
M2i Life Science=E2=80=99s biocontrol products7), or even new technologies =
(Prophesee=E2=80=99s retina-inspired camera8, or Biomemory=E2=80=99s DNA-ba=
sed data storage9).&nbsp; <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D=
"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Ecosystems don=E2=80=99t fav=
our simplified systems <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" =
class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Nevertheless, biomimicry is sti=
ll not yet a term that is well understood. And it should be known that it i=
s not currently being used with the intention of greening any process that =
even remotely resembles a living object. =E2=80=9CWe call this trend biomiw=
ashing,=E2=80=9D says Kalina Raskin. More and more =E2=80=9Cnature-inspired=
=E2=80=9D products are appearing on the market, and they have more to do wi=
th storytelling than with a scientific approach. =E2=80=9CThe use of biomim=
etic terminology without any real scientific basis undermines the credibili=
ty of the approach=E2=80=9D, insists the director of Ceebios. <!----><!----=
></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-ins=
erted"> Biomimicry is now subject to the ISO 18458 standard, which provides=
 a framework to use the term. Ceebios, in partnership with ADEME and the Sa=
int-Etienne eco-design cluster, is also preparing =E2=80=9Can introductory =
guide to biomimicry for eco-design=E2=80=9D. For Kalina Raskin, the aim is =
to =E2=80=9Cexplain the importance of the approach and encourage manufactur=
ers to measure the biomimicry component in their processes=E2=80=9D. <!----=
><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-s=
tar-inserted"> 500px Photo ID: 107350355&nbsp;- <!----><!----></p><p _ngcon=
tent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Emmanu=
el Delannoy suggests going even further. =E2=80=9CEcosystems don=E2=80=99t =
favour simplified systems,=E2=80=9D he points out. They tend towards comple=
xity and diversification, establishing balances and sharing resources. This=
 goes against the grain of current industrial production methods, which dis=
courage diversity.&nbsp; The specialist imagines systems whose efficiency w=
ill not be measured on performance alone, but capable of moving towards gre=
ater complexity, tolerating diversity and being more frugal. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s not necessarily the optimisation of an output that counts, but the =
balance of the system=E2=80=9D, he explains. He is thinking, for example, o=
f logistics systems that combine complementary solutions to adapt to differ=
ent conditions on the ground. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c305900511=
1=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Biomimicry could also de=
velop by broadening its models. The biological objects most studied from a =
biomimetic angle are the gecko, the shark, the lotus, the eagle, the kingfi=
sher, the Japanese fugu, spider silk, the flipper of the humpback whale=E2=
=80=A6 =E2=80=9CExperts estimate that the Earth is home to more than 20 mil=
lion species. But only 2 million have been identified, and very few have be=
en studied at the interdisciplinary interfaces,=E2=80=9D points out Kalina =
Raskin. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-=
text-line ng-star-inserted"> A fast-growing concept <!----><!----></p><p _n=
gcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-inserted"><!-=
---><br _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"ng-star-inserted"><!----></=
p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line ng-star-insert=
ed"> Today, advocates of biomimicry want to incorporate the method into ind=
ustrial toolkits. =E2=80=9CTo move from being a novelty to a routine proces=
s, we need to increase the number of biological models=E2=80=9D, adds Kalin=
a Raskin. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"quer=
y-text-line ng-star-inserted"> In response, Ceebios has set up a programme =
with the Museum national d=E2=80=99Histoire naturelle (MNHN) funded by the =
Banque Publique d=E2=80=99Investissement. The aim is to bring together indu=
stry and research laboratories to jointly address the issues at stake. =E2=
=80=9CFor example, we need new antifouling coatings, materials with better =
mechanical resistance, and new agents for colour opacity. To understand the=
se industrial issues, we are working with researchers at the MNHN to find o=
rganisms whose biology we can examine=E2=80=9D, explains Kalina Raskin. <!-=
---><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query-text-line n=
g-star-inserted"> Progress is being made in the development of the concept.=
 However, in order to become truly established, it will have to overcome a =
major risk. =E2=80=9CThere is a strong bias towards technological solutions=
, the idea that there is a solution to every problem, and a technological o=
ne at that, without taking a critical look at it=E2=80=9D, explains Emmanue=
l Delannoy, =E2=80=9Cthis kind of thinking is not compatible with the ethic=
s of biomimicry. =E2=80=9CWe must always ask ourselves whether it is really=
 necessary, by taking into account the solution to a real current need and =
the human and ecological challenges of the future,=E2=80=9D insists the spe=
cialist. <!----><!----></p><p _ngcontent-ng-c3059005111=3D"" class=3D"query=
-text-line ng-star-inserted"> Agn=C3=A8s Vernet <!----><!----></p><p _ngcon=
